If you're not going to have the dialogue be intelligible, there's no point in having sound.  That's not to say I couldn't hear *anything*, but the beginning of the movie, where a lot of the exposition comes in, was unintelligible.  

I  like a movie that makes you think.  I liked Inception and Memento for that reason.  I even liked Interstellar *despite* the sound problems.  But TENET just took it too far.  It was too incomprehensible, and the thing is, it looks like that was by design.

If you ever have watched the 2003 indie movie "The Room" then you know that that movie was labeled as one of the worst films ever made. However it was said by the actor and director of the movie himself, Tom Wiseau, that the movie was intended to be black humor, hinting that the awkward dialogues and bad acting were put there deliberately to create confusion and was not meant to be taken seriously.

TENET felt like such a movie. But what worries me the most is that TENET was probably in fact a serious attempt at being a pretentious movie. The plot and dialogue were absolute nonsensical that it slowly became comedic, were it not that Nolan intentions probably was to make an intelligent movie, however done it so that it was deceiving and played games with the audience perception, but underestimated the intellect of the audience, meaning you cannot cover up nonsensical plotlines with confusing dialogues. Now I am all for absurd dialogues in the style of maybe like Quentin Tarantino's movies, but it needs to be executed smartly, not randomly.

Therefore as a deliberate black comedy, I would have given this movie a 9, if it was intended that way, but I think not. So I give it 3 stars and this movie might end up in the list as one of the worst films ever made next to "The Room"....

I think that Nolan amps up the audio over the dialogue as an immersion technique. When he does this, I immediately get the impression that you're in a very loud space, and you're trying to have a convo with someone, and because I always get that impression, it immerses me more in the scene. That coupled with the way he uses the IMAX shots to make the audience feels like a part of the scene works... for me. It's not very practical, as a lot of people will not be impacted this way. However, it's very intelligent, yes it has a tradeoff, but Nolan knows that you're more than likely going to revisit his film, in which case you'll pay more attention to the dialogue this time around (subtitles lol). 

My only grievance with this film is Washington's reaction to being introduced to inversion. I think up to that point, he had not been exposed to terrorism so other-wordly, so to speak, and his reaction was not consistent with the typical recoiling human response indicative of ignorance. It was too quickly accepted. Other than that, this was an epic movie.

If you ever have watched the 2003 indie movie "The Room" then you know that that movie was labeled as one of the worst films ever made. However it was said by the actor and director of the movie himself, Tom Wiseau, that the movie was intended to be black humor, hinting that the awkward dialogues and bad acting were put there deliberately to create confusion and was not meant to be taken seriously.

TENET felt like such a movie. But what worries me the most is that TENET was probably in fact a serious attempt at being a pretentious movie. The plot and dialogue were absolute nonsensical that it slowly became comedic, were it not that Nolan intentions probably was to make an intelligent movie, however done it so that it was deceiving and played games with the audience perception, but underestimated the intellect of the audience, meaning you cannot cover up nonsensical plotlines with confusing dialogues. Now I am all for absurd dialogues in the style of maybe like Quentin Tarantino's movies, but it needs to be executed smartly, not randomly.

Therefore as a deliberate black comedy, I would have given this movie a 9, if it was intended that way, but I think not. So I give it 3 stars and this movie might end up in the list as one of the worst films ever made next to "The Room"....

I'm a Nolan fan and usually love his movies. I avoided everything about Tenet before watching it last night. For me, it was far from his best work. I don't have a problem with it being complex or needing to watch it more than once to fully understand it. To me, my biggest problem with Tenet is that nothing is really personal or meaningful for the characters. We barely get to know them or even care about them. 

My whole thought the entire movie was why does The protagonist care or have to loose? What's at stake for him? One of the reasons given in the movie is to "save the world" which to me is extremely generic and cliche. The other is that he seems extremely vested in the girl and her son but why? There's no real love story or deep connection there at all. 

That's where this movie really lost me. Yes there was really cool things to look at and the score was amazing but I didn't walk away feeling any deep connection between the characters nor did I care for them much. 

In Inception, Dom is trying to get home to be with his children. And he carries the burden of his wife killing herself because of something he did. A father reuniting with his children if the mission is accomplished or going to jail for life if he fails gives great motivation and shows the consequences. Tenet has none of this. It's pretty much a guy trying to save the world bc it's his job. The consequences is the world ending, okay I get it... But it doesn't really matter if we don't care about anyone on screen. The main character really has no other goal or anything to loose other than just doing his job.

My honest opinion on this movie is this. Leaving the theater after watching Inception left me with questions about the characters, the overall state of mind that Hobb has at the conclusion, lessons learned for each member of the squad, and what was to become of the man who accepted a lie that his father loved him and that he wanted him to live his life the way that he wanted, what was to become of this man. See with inception, there was a heft that came with each of its characters and development of them as well as the plot. The plot was complicated, yet not so convoluted to the point where the viewer was left with questions about the plot itself, most of us understood what was happening, it was more of understanding the deeper side of the psyche of the characters (hence, the ever so infamous question, is Hobb still dreaming at the end of the movie.) 

With this movie, I felt as if Christopher found that the success of Inception hinged on the fact that some of the plot points being complicated made the movie enjoyable, but that isn't the case. Tenets major problem is that there are extreme complexities within the rules and regulations of how the world works, and these complexities are thrown at us at a blistering speed that nearly robs us of the enjoyment of an easy going movie experience. 

Don't get me wrong, damn near every Nolan film has some sort of depth and has its own twists and turns, but Tenet just felt as if Nolan wanted to make the most complex, convoluted, and hard to follow story in recent memory, and in that he succeeded. But where Inception shined with character, and development, Tenet completely lacks these same traits and feels more like a giant meal with too many things added to it, yet has no flavor at all.

Pacing for this movie was horrid. Jeremy got it spot on, they explain the complicated things in this movie flawlessly, but the simple things, such as character development and just setting the scenes are poorly thrown together. On top of that, whats a simple throw away line of a mom wanting to remove her son from a asshole billionaire becomes the entire driving thread for the entire movie. Whats worse, it's only reinforced or made important by a simple "you don't know what its like to be a mother" line. While the ENTIRE FATE OF THE WORLD IS AT STAKE fyi. Back to the pacing, it starts off fast and does not slow down. I get it, its a thriller, edge of your seat ride. but the simple editing is so hard to keep track of. There's a portion where John David Washington's character begs for a spot at a exclusive dinner for the following day, -30 seconds later he's at the exclusive dinner and immediately leaves, -30 seconds later its the following day and the person he just met is speaking to/of him as if they've been lifelong friends. That break neck speed is the entire movie, even in exposition logs that should take its time to allow the audience to process the very important information that was always being conversed at a million miles a second. The conversations are very to the point, and leaves little to actual world building other than a few flashback sequences. (The reason behind this was explained in film, but just because you warn the bank before you rob them does not make the crime any less punishable.)

But. it is a Nolan film after all,
It is a good movie. If you can keep up and hold onto key information through out the film, you will be thoroughly rewarded come the film's climatic last act. Even keener eyes would pick up the stories loosely predictable patterns -(not a complaint) before the characters do themselves. Once you start to develop the way of thinking that the characters are forced to learn themselves in order to operate in this world, the movie becomes a lot more fun. The story is unique, the actions scenes are phenomenal, and the ending predictable, but in a good payoff-ish way.

As Jeremy said, This is most likely a 3 1/2 hour movie that was compressed down to 2 1/2. Not to mention I'm positive the pandemic is largely responsible for some of the poor editing choices with the editors working largely from home and a potential delay between communication with the director. If there ever is a "directors cut" this movie would easily be on par with movies such a The Dark Knight and Interstellar. This isn't the "Movie industry savior" as some hoped it would be, but it'll definitely get your heart racing in key moments.

His sound mix method worked for Dunkirk, because the buried dialogue made sense for how bombastic war would be... but, when you are watching a thriller and can‚Äôt pick up the story beats, that‚Äôs when it‚Äôs a problem. Yes, I got the over-arching plot of Tenet, but the details and why characters were doing specific things was lost on me. I know he doesn‚Äôt like to ADR his movies, but that‚Äôs at direct odds with shooting on IMAX cameras that make a ton of noise while recording. I‚Äôm all about pushing the envelope of what‚Äôs expected, but the sound mix made this movie a frustrating experience for me and my wife. She has bad hearing and thought it was just her, but I reassured her it was not.

In terms of complexity, Tenet makes Primer look like Timecop, but the sound mix WAS way off, and there's no way that the characters believably had these fast, straight-ahead, conversations on how this all works without people being occasionally tripped up and making mistakes. I doubt that Nolan actually violated any of the rules he established within the story, but the story, and dialogue, unfold too quickly to get it all in one viewing.

Since you asked, Jeremy, here‚Äôs my ranking for Nolan movies

1. Inception
His most complete movie. Complex plotting, decent character work, emotional undertones, mind-blowing visuals and direction.
2. The Dark Knight
Unstoppably great on every level, but lacking the flair and originality that puts Inception on top for me.
3. Dunkirk
Visually brilliant, remarkably intense, painting in broad swathes of emotion rather than an emotional core of a relationship, and his usual time-switching style makes this thoroughly engaging and powerful.
4. Interstellar
Delves deeper into the human side of Nolan‚Äôs characters, it possesses astounding visuals and easily understood characters, with a simpler plot line that nevertheless plays well with the ideas of fate and family.
5. Tenet
Pure story, pure spectacle, gripping and tense, with a intricate plot to be pieced together alongside set-piece brilliance.
6. The Prestige
Intriguing and entertaining, it wows with revelation after revelation as it races with parallel stories towards a series of wonderful twist endings.
7. Memento
Groundbreaking and smart, Nolan‚Äôs breakthrough effort is still cleverly designed and possesses just enough hidden depth to be a little more than just a gimmick.
8. The Dark Knight Rises
Flawed but still a worthy and emotionally resonant conclusion to the Dark Knight Trilogy.
9. Batman Begins
Nolan redefines the superhero genre in a competent character study of Batman‚Äôs origins.
10. Insomnia
Well-made, if not particularly interesting or original.
11. The Following
Intriguing concepts abound in his debut, which though decent enough to watch lacks the finesse or the true subtlety to handle a smaller film.

I've seen it twice now and it's a mess. It's even worse the 2nd time around. I was hoping it would get better but alas...it did exactly the opposite.  All of its flaws were accentuated. It's an incoherent, convoluted, incomprehensible mess. We just don't care about the characters. There's no central dramatic spine or character driven idea that we care about. It's all just visual spectacle. 

It feels like Nolan had a 4 hour movie somewhere but he's had to cram in everything he wanted to tell, say and do into 2 1/2 hours. Doesn't work. the whole enterprise just feels terribly rushed.

Most of the dialogue scenes are risible and most disappointing of all (and a cardinal sin for a Nolan film) I was bored watching it again. Even the action scenes didn‚Äôt excite me the 2nd time around.

And you miss one expositional talk scene (and please...when is Nolan going to fix his sound mix? It's just awful. SFX are ear shatteringly loud and in yer face and then the more important dialogue scenes you have to strain to decipher) and you have no idea what's going on for the next 15 minutes. Just awful.

And that catamaran scene...WTF was that!? They're out on the boat and I thought oh yeah here we go...a decent action scene...And then they started talking!! Expositional talking! What!!?? I'm thinking 'what are they doing? Why are they talking about important stuff now I can hardly hear them. They've got helmets on and are talking through friggin microphones ffs!' Ludicrous.

Lee Smith's absence is notable too. I thought it was terribly edited, especially the interminable dialogue scenes in the first half an hour. Really disjointed and jarring.

And as for John David Washington...Well I thought he was awful. No gravitas at all. Terribly miscast. He was even worse the 2nd time round. And you've got Kenneth Branagh hamming it up like no tomorrow. He's almost laughable. And I know three dimensional female characters aren't exactly Nolan's strong suit but please...do you think we could have a bit more from Elizabeth Debicki (who does an ok job mind you. Don't get me wrong) other than "I have a son"...who by the way we never discover and we are never privy to their relationship so how can we even care. Pattinson was decent enough and Aaron Taylor-Johnson had presence but was criminally underused.

I could go on but suffice to say...It's disappointing. I was expecting more. It's certainly not as bad as Interstellar but it's probably his duddest film after that...possibly in the realms of The Dark Knight Rises.

I have a theory about the movie that provides context for a lot of people‚Äôs issues with Tenet, including the sound mixing. The sound mixing is on purpose. Throughout the movie the spies repeat an idea so much it seems to be a theme: you only know what you need to know. This happens repeatedly. Team members are given only a part of the information. The sound mixing makes it so that the audience only knows what we need to know WHEN we need to know. When first encounter a scenario, the mixing muffled certain dialogue. When we encounter that scene again (spoilers) from a different perspective, I noticed the muffled dialogue was repeated more clearly. The sound mixing purposely lets us experience the same thing as the Protagonist on purpose. I think the confusing way in which we get the information is so we experience it‚Äôs unfolding like him.

I don't want to encourage anyone to risk their lives. The only reason why I saw TENET is because the cinema I went to had the proper safety measures and because I live in Rome, where the COVID-19 cases aren't as high as other places (at least for now). If your situation is similar to mine, that's a whole other conversation. Now, the plot revolves around a secret mission. So secret that, a couple of times, the agents and the employers discuss it in public, including a ferry where they're surrounded by people. Wait, what? Like most of Christopher Nolan's works, we have a complicated plot involving a lot of real science and philosophy in our hands. Unfortunately, there's something missing that was present in his previous projects: Strong emotions that drive the main characters through their journey (a husband trying to kill his wife's murderer, a father who misses his son and daughter, a father who misses his daughter and I guess his son too, etc...). Here, we learn nothing about our hero. And don't tell me that's the point, like in DUNKIRK. That was because the soldiers served as vessels for the viewers to insert ourselves into, in order to feel what it's like to be in a war zone. Not to mention that 2017 hit was designed to be a complete visual and auditory experience. This one balances the images and the audio the same way most movies do, and the protagonist is presented as a real person. Without knowing what motivates him on a personal level (instead of just wanting to save the world), I couldn't connect with him and, by extension, with the movie. Also, he and a lot of the other characters are similar in terms of personality, whether they're displaying their inner strength, their intelligence or their sense of humor, so they don't stand out, unlike INCEPTION with its group of distinct individuals. Speaking of that 2010 classic, it didn't matter that the events were written as a traditional heist film, because they took place inside people's dreams. All kinds of unpredictable and imaginative things happened in each environment. Here, a special element is introduced early on, but it's not used to the fullest until the 2nd half. The 1st half is a traditional spy film (and not a very interesting one) that occasionally turns into science fiction. It would be easy to dismiss Jennifer Lame's editing as choppy. I mean, I can't remember a shot lasting more than 5 or even 2 seconds (to be fair, I wasn't actually timing them). There are even moments where a character is doing something and in the very next shot they're doing something else in another part of the room, indicating that at least a couple of seconds have passed. However, that and the near total lack of establishing shots makes me think that her hands were tied and she was just doing her best to reduce the running time down to 150 minutes. Honestly, I would've preferred it if she had deleted full scenes. Trust me: Not all of them were indispensable. No other aspect about this production is bad at all, but without something to get invested in, what's the point?

I don't watch trailers very often. The only time I do is when I'm on the fence about going to see it. Tenet hit at a good time for me. Not only was it a CN film but also it was the first movie to come out as the cinema reopened. Thoroughly enjoyed this movie. I was a bit worn down by the length but I'm also on a shit sleep scheduled ATM so I kind of blame that. The way they do the traveling in this movie blow me away. You've seen it dozens of times but this was fresh and like Jeremy said there aren't very many fresh movies out there. Most just play it safe or have a quick twist thrown in at the end.

The only other movies I've seen lately that were fresh to me were 1917 and JoJo rabbit. They've left me at least feeling something new. There are very few directors that are willing to step out nowadays either due to cancel culture and fear of backlash from the internet brigade. When watching JoJo rabbit all I could think of was how did this get made? Every time I saw Hitler doing random shit I wondered who had a stroke on the day this got pitched to have it gotten into production. It's the type of film that would enrage a mob and get boycotted on twitter with some stupid hashtag before they even got done with filming but it didn't. And it was great. Good writing, characters and a different perspective. Even though the end message was the nazi's were bad usually anything that even looks like bad people showing good characteristics is enough to send people off.

Sorry for the rant. It went a bit off base towards the end but I feel strongly about creative freedom and you don't get too much of that anymore.

The thing that surprised me most about this movie is that it really is nothing more than Christopher Nolan doing James Bond with the time inversion as little more than a McGuffin. Inversion is never really used to its full extent - not the way Nolan embraced the dream concept for Inception. 

The problem with this being a Bond film is that the action scenes, with a few notable exceptions, are really not that great and can't compete with what the best of the genre has to offer. Which is understandable - Nolan is more of an idea director, not an action director. His ideas are always more interesting than what is actually happening. Unfortunately, in this movie the ideas aren't as fully explored as they usually are in his films - leaving you with a feeling of bland emptiness. Plus it still had that Chris Nolan emotionless, cold objective observer feel that most of his films have.

Again, you are right, the sound balance was WAY off. Overall, I liked the film, but it just lacked much impact.

I also think sound recording is often secondary for Nolan, which is like a film school taboo. I was a film student and my professors agreed that often the worst element of student films is the sound because they spend so much time forcusing on how the film looks and not enough time worrying about how it sounds. And Nolan is known for being an economical director, his productions pretty much never go beyond their filming schedule. He always finishes productions on time or ahead of schedule. So I think that's why the sound in his films is always one of the worst elements. The recording of the sound on the day-of seems to take a backseat for him compared to everything else.

One of the few times where i've been waiting for days to see Jeremy review a movie i saw days ago... HAHA! Seems them masks didn't help ya much Murica. HAHA! But anyways, seems i loved the movie far more then you Jeremy. I was half expecting this to be Awesometacular or atleast Buy it on Blu-ray worthy. I watched the two first trailers. And i honestly didn't know what to expect outside from that so i went in expecting a good Nolan movie. And that's what i got. I think if invert was the constant of this movie it would be a bit too much. I genuinly like how we experience the logic of it as the main character does. And i liked the characters and the dialogue. I'll admit the Russian badguy was very stereotypical to a point where he kinda made me laugh. But he still did a good job. But this movie does so well the whole upping it every act. Like it goes from a spy movie with some inverted bits in it to just all out timy whimy madness. Towards the end when you finaly start putting the pices together it's just like ''WOW!''. So i loved the film. I gave it a full score. All the actors did a great job for the most part. The story had me hooked. It was a true Nolan movie. I find it hard to put it on a list of top Nolan movies however. I don't really know... But i think Interstellar is my favorite simply because space is my thing. But it's also genuinly an Amazing film. The Dark Knight is probably second to it with Inception following that... But after that i just don't know what order to place the movies. All i know is that i have yet to see a Christopher Nolan movie i didn't love. Nolan at this point is just that Director i will allways go see the movies for. I know that his movies are cinematic masterpices trough and trough. And this one was no different. That final act tho.... Once everything comes together and you get it and the action pumps up.... It's so fucking insane! That final act is... Mindbendingly awesome! It's totally unique! And the ending... Well, it's confusing! But also not really. It's.... Hard to explain is what it is. But you get it if you pay atention. What ever, i'm allready pumped to see what Nolan does next. I mean the man has done ilusions, his done dream mind fuckery, his done time and space bending with Black holes and worm holes. And now hes done  timy whimy fuckery with reversed time flows and shit... What's next? It's kind of hard to imagine. Personaly i don't feel like TENET needs a sequel. It does wrap up it's story. So if there is a sequel it would have to be a new adventure in the same universe and maybe the same characters. I wouldn't mind it. But Nolan does run the risk of the not so good sequel syndrom if he does that. I think there would have had to be a door left open in the movie. And yeah, there are doors. But those doors are for ''The Adventures of_________'' really. The plot itself does wrap. So Nolan's next film should probably and will probably be something new. But at this point, what? It's hard to imagine. Maybe he'll mess around with Gravity? Maybe he'll do his take on something else that has been done? Imagine a post aphocalyptic spy movies with AI that has a heist plot.... I mean, all Nolan movies are in a sense a Heist. Well, most of them. Time heist, gangster heist, dream heist... HAHA! Or maybe he just gives up and makes a Childrens movie. I would watch that tho.

Well, I don't know where to start. For most part I agree with you, it was definitely original take, no doubt about it. It also made me think that it's something I've never seen before when I left cinema. But that's where our similarities end i feel. I was very confused by set up and explanation of the world portrayed in the movie. And when I say confused, I mean I had no idea wtf was going on. I had general idea of concept , of course, and by no means I'm an average popcorn flicker , I love challenging movies ,but boy does this movie confused me. And not only me, when it finished and I looked at the audience, everyone was confused with a wtf  just happened written all over their faces. The story was rushed, without proper explanation I feel, which caused chain reaction of bloody confusion. The more I tried to get my head around it, the minute I thought I understood what was going on, Nolan threw new piece at me, that shattered everything I knew. And I'm afraid for me it wasn't in a good way. I felt alienated when I watched it, because I couldn't fully understand what was going on, as my friend whom with I went to see it, and rest of audience also. On top of that, sounds effects? Man, it was just overdone. I get the idea behind it, it is supposed to make you feel like you are actually on scene, but in a movie like that, where every bit is very important to understand, muffled dialogue doesn't help,it's actually doing opposite. It actually made me angry at times, that I can't understand what actors were saying, as it was obviously crucial in understanding the concept. The cinematography was amazing, as well as special effects, that's a standard in Nolan's movies. Actors played it amazing also, although I felt Pattison wasn't given enough attention, given how crucial of a character he happened to be in the end. It could've been amazing movie, the idea behind it is fantastic, but for me it was way overcomplicated on screen and sounds score has ruined it for me completely, rending it unwatchable. Maybe if I watch it another 10 times, then I'll change my mind, but as a one off in cinema I can't give it more then c minus. Also I just wanted to thank you for your reviews and all the work you do here, I think it's fantastic. Keep up, cheers.

I‚Äôve been thinking about how to approach this review on Tenet without giving the impression of bashing the movie or hating on it. Cause I did like this movie but I certainly have a lot to say. Let‚Äôs start with this, I was like everyone else with Tenet. I was super excited, who wouldn‚Äôt be! Christopher Nolan directing, big budget summer blockbuster, with a complex plot, awesome trailer and a great cast! I‚Äôve been waiting for this movie for a long time and as soon as I found a showtime for my city I decided I had to go. So I saw Tenet and I have to say, this is a Christopher Nolan movie. It has his style of direction all over it. The complex and dense plot, big action spectacles and a long runtime. Will people like it, most likely unfortunate for me not so much. What really bothered me about this movie was the plot and how Nolan told this story. It didn‚Äôt feel cohesive or even understandable really but rather very confusing, rushed and the outcome of it all made me question what was the purpose of all that just happened. Even some of the plot points of this movie that kinda make sense doesn‚Äôt actually do. Like I didn‚Äôt really know much about the villain or his goals and there wasn‚Äôt enough character development to him other than a cliche evil plan, him being just a jerk but the actor who portrays him did a good job. The acting of this character gave an impression of unintentionally being funny and entertaining. But a lot of this movie felt like it was trying to be an extravaganza of action scenes, set pieces and dazzling spectacles. Luckily It does accomplish that though, a lot of the times. The action is really well done and does a lot of the spectacles. I just wish that the movie presented a more compelling story, because it felt as though it was kinda trying too. The story, plotting and even sometimes the screenplay felt so jumbled throughout the entire runtime. It tries to be so intellectual and complex but at the end it didn‚Äôt succeed at it. Overall Tenet wasn‚Äôt as great as I hoped for but, big and sometimes fun action scenes, good acting, sound design, and the look of the movie are all positives for Tenet. Maybe I just wasn‚Äôt smart enough to appreciate all this movie had to offer and that‚Äôs unfortunate, but I did have some fun with Tenet and think most people will enjoy it.

I'm sorry but I found this one of Nolan's weakest movies because as good as the concept and visuals were, it was completely undercut by the motivation of the villain. They literally found a way to invert and communicate back and forth through time and with all the possibilities that you can explore with that concept, you go with a guy that's terminally ill and wants to use it to destroy the world?! Like not even rule the world, literally destroy the world and everyone in it because if he can't live no one else should be able to--how on earth are we to buy that even his own henchmen would go along with this? His upper tier henchmen knew what the end goal was and they're all just fighting to die for one guy's delusions? We've seen such plots from lesser films, but I expect way more from Nolan. 

It would be like if Palpatine was somehow terminally ill and instead of having the empire "rule the galaxy," he told them to destroy the rebellion and then when they're done to go commit suicide because if he won't be alive to see their victory, none of them should be. Once word got out that was his motivation, the empire itself would have rebelled against him. 

I normally enjoy Nolan's twists, but this one felt like he passed off explaining the villain's motivations to M. Night Shyamalan üòï.
